</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Rupture of the vasa vasorum into the media of the aortic wall results in an aortic intramural hematoma. Characteristic findings of an aortic intramural hematoma include a crescentic hyperattenuating fluid collection at unenhanced computed tomography (CT) and a smooth, nonenhancing, thickened aortic wall at contrast material–enhanced CT. The CT appearance of untreated intramural hematomas evolves over time, and decreased attenuation is a clue to the chronicity of a hematoma. CT is particularly useful for evaluating aortic intramural hematomas because it allows their differentiation from aortic dissections, which have similar clinical manifestations, and permits an exact determination of their location—crucial information for surgical planning. On the basis of CT findings, some hematomas may be expected to resolve spontaneously, whereas others may be identified as posing a high risk for serious complications such as aortic dissection, aneurysm, and rupture. Appropriate clinical management is aided by accurate recognition of diagnostically specific CT features and awareness of their significance.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2009</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.293085122">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.293085122">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18c01a.jpeg" height="773" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F1A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1a.</b>  Diagrams show the pathogenesis of aortic intramural hematoma. Hemorrhage resulting from rupture of the vasa vasorum weakens the media of the aortic wall <b>(a)</b> and leads to enlargement of the aortic diameter <b>(b)</b>. In an intramural hematoma, unlike an aortic dissection or penetrating ulcer, the intima remains intact.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F1A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18c01b.jpeg" height="748" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F1B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1b.</b>  Diagrams show the pathogenesis of aortic intramural hematoma. Hemorrhage resulting from rupture of the vasa vasorum weakens the media of the aortic wall <b>(a)</b> and leads to enlargement of the aortic diameter <b>(b)</b>. In an intramural hematoma, unlike an aortic dissection or penetrating ulcer, the intima remains intact.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F1B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g02x.jpeg" height="1800" width="1389" aria-labelledby="F2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2.</b>  CT features of aortic intramural hematoma. Unenhanced axial image shows intimal calcifications in a curvilinear configuration (arrowheads) and a crescentic hyperattenuating intramural fluid collection (<b>*</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g03x.jpeg" height="1800" width="1334" aria-labelledby="F3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3.</b>  CT features of aortic intramural hematoma. Contrast material–enhanced axial image depicts a smooth, nonenhancing, crescentic region of aortic wall thickening (arrowheads) without a spiraling intimal flap.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g04a.jpeg" height="1505" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4a.</b>  Change in CT appearance with evolution of aortic intramural hematoma. <b>(a)</b> Unenhanced axial CT image obtained at initial presentation shows an intramural fluid collection (arrow) with attenuation higher than that of intraluminal blood, a finding indicative of acute hematoma. <b>(b)</b> Unenhanced axial CT image obtained 1 month later shows the same collection (arrow), now with attenuation identical to that of intraluminal blood. This finding is indicative of greater age of the hematoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F4A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g04b.jpeg" height="1536" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4b.</b>  Change in CT appearance with evolution of aortic intramural hematoma. <b>(a)</b> Unenhanced axial CT image obtained at initial presentation shows an intramural fluid collection (arrow) with attenuation higher than that of intraluminal blood, a finding indicative of acute hematoma. <b>(b)</b> Unenhanced axial CT image obtained 1 month later shows the same collection (arrow), now with attenuation identical to that of intraluminal blood. This finding is indicative of greater age of the hematoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F4B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g05x.jpeg" height="1252" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5.</b>  Transesophageal 120° echocardiogram obtained with the transducer at the level of the midesophagus demonstrates a smooth, 5-mm-thick hypoechoic layer (arrows) within the wall of the ascending aorta. (Courtesy of Amy Spooner, MD, Boston, Mass.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g06a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1571" aria-labelledby="F6A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6a.</b>  Subacute aortic intramural hematoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted gradient-echo (white-blood) MR image depicts an intramural fluid collection with intermediate hyperintensity of signal in comparison with the signal intensity of intraluminal blood. <b>(b)</b> Axial T1-weighted spin-echo (black-blood) MR image shows hyperintensity of signal in the intramural collection compared with that in intraluminal blood. These findings are suggestive of subacute chronicity.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F6A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g06b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1563" aria-labelledby="F6B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6b.</b>  Subacute aortic intramural hematoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted gradient-echo (white-blood) MR image depicts an intramural fluid collection with intermediate hyperintensity of signal in comparison with the signal intensity of intraluminal blood. <b>(b)</b> Axial T1-weighted spin-echo (black-blood) MR image shows hyperintensity of signal in the intramural collection compared with that in intraluminal blood. These findings are suggestive of subacute chronicity.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F6B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g07x.jpeg" height="1282" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7.</b>  Aortic wall thickening in a patient with retroperitoneal fibrosis. Contrast-enhanced axial CT image shows mildly enhancing, irregular circumferential aortic wall thickening with a lobulated border, findings that are uncharacteristic of aortic intramural hematoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g08x.jpeg" height="1648" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8.</b>  Adherent thrombus mimicking aortic intramural hematoma. Contrast-enhanced axial CT image shows a focal eccentric nonenhancing structure that encroaches on the aortic lumen. The irregular intraluminal surface and its location in the abdominal aorta are not characteristic of an aortic intramural hematoma. Moreover, the wall calcifications are located along the outer border of the aorta rather than displaced toward the center of the lumen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g09x.jpeg" height="1800" width="1225" aria-labelledby="F9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9.</b>  Aortic dissection. Reconstructed 3D CT image demonstrates longitudinal spiraling of the intimal flap, a feature that is not present in aortic intramural hematoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g10x.jpeg" height="1800" width="1402" aria-labelledby="F10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10.</b>  Penetrating aortic ulcer. Contrast-enhanced axial CT image shows a focal contrast-material-filled pouch (arrow) that communicates with the aortic lumen but extends outward, beyond its normal circumference.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g11a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1507" aria-labelledby="F11A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11a.</b>  Comparison of both unenhanced <b>(a, b)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(c, d)</b> axial CT images obtained at presentation (<b>a</b> and <b>c</b> at a higher level than <b>b</b> and <b>d</b>) with contrast-enhanced images obtained at similar levels 2 months later <b>(e, f)</b> shows resolution of a type B aortic intramural hematoma after conservative management.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F11A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g11b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1377" aria-labelledby="F11B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11b.</b>  Comparison of both unenhanced <b>(a, b)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(c, d)</b> axial CT images obtained at presentation (<b>a</b> and <b>c</b> at a higher level than <b>b</b> and <b>d</b>) with contrast-enhanced images obtained at similar levels 2 months later <b>(e, f)</b> shows resolution of a type B aortic intramural hematoma after conservative management.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F11B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g11c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1500" aria-labelledby="F11C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11c.</b>  Comparison of both unenhanced <b>(a, b)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(c, d)</b> axial CT images obtained at presentation (<b>a</b> and <b>c</b> at a higher level than <b>b</b> and <b>d</b>) with contrast-enhanced images obtained at similar levels 2 months later <b>(e, f)</b> shows resolution of a type B aortic intramural hematoma after conservative management.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F11C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g11d.jpeg" height="1800" width="1397" aria-labelledby="F11D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11d.</b>  Comparison of both unenhanced <b>(a, b)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(c, d)</b> axial CT images obtained at presentation (<b>a</b> and <b>c</b> at a higher level than <b>b</b> and <b>d</b>) with contrast-enhanced images obtained at similar levels 2 months later <b>(e, f)</b> shows resolution of a type B aortic intramural hematoma after conservative management.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F11D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g11e.jpeg" height="1800" width="1512" aria-labelledby="F11E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11e.</b>  Comparison of both unenhanced <b>(a, b)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(c, d)</b> axial CT images obtained at presentation (<b>a</b> and <b>c</b> at a higher level than <b>b</b> and <b>d</b>) with contrast-enhanced images obtained at similar levels 2 months later <b>(e, f)</b> shows resolution of a type B aortic intramural hematoma after conservative management.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F11E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11F" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g11f.jpeg" height="1800" width="1379" aria-labelledby="F11F" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11f.</b>  Comparison of both unenhanced <b>(a, b)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(c, d)</b> axial CT images obtained at presentation (<b>a</b> and <b>c</b> at a higher level than <b>b</b> and <b>d</b>) with contrast-enhanced images obtained at similar levels 2 months later <b>(e, f)</b> shows resolution of a type B aortic intramural hematoma after conservative management.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F11F">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g12a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1452" aria-labelledby="F12A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12a.</b>  Progression of aortic intramural hematoma to aortic dissection. <b>(a)</b> Unenhanced axial CT image obtained at presentation depicts a type B aortic intramural hematoma (arrow). No evidence of extraluminal contrast material was seen at contrast-enhanced CT, and the hematoma was treated with conservative management. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced axial CT image obtained 1 month later shows an enhancing ulcerlike projection (arrow), a finding suggestive of a new intimal tear. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced axial CT image obtained 2 months later shows overt dissection (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F12A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g12b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1297" aria-labelledby="F12B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12b.</b>  Progression of aortic intramural hematoma to aortic dissection. <b>(a)</b> Unenhanced axial CT image obtained at presentation depicts a type B aortic intramural hematoma (arrow). No evidence of extraluminal contrast material was seen at contrast-enhanced CT, and the hematoma was treated with conservative management. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced axial CT image obtained 1 month later shows an enhancing ulcerlike projection (arrow), a finding suggestive of a new intimal tear. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced axial CT image obtained 2 months later shows overt dissection (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F12B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g12c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1452" aria-labelledby="F12C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12c.</b>  Progression of aortic intramural hematoma to aortic dissection. <b>(a)</b> Unenhanced axial CT image obtained at presentation depicts a type B aortic intramural hematoma (arrow). No evidence of extraluminal contrast material was seen at contrast-enhanced CT, and the hematoma was treated with conservative management. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced axial CT image obtained 1 month later shows an enhancing ulcerlike projection (arrow), a finding suggestive of a new intimal tear. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced axial CT image obtained 2 months later shows overt dissection (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F12C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g13a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1460" aria-labelledby="F13A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13a.</b>  Type A aortic intramural hematoma at high risk for progression to dissection. <b>(a, b)</b> Unenhanced <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(b)</b> axial CT images demonstrate an ascending aortic intramural hematoma, with a maximal aortic diameter of 6.4 cm. The implicit high risk of progression to aortic dissection prompted surgical treatment. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced axial CT image obtained after surgical repair shows a normal caliber of the ascending aorta. hematomas, with frequent surveillance imaging and timely surgical repair in patients with complications. Further support for these recommendations may be found in the demographic characteristics of those affected by intramural hematoma (typically, older adults) and the potentially high morbidity and mortality associated with aortic surgery in this population (<a href="#R5" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="R5">5</a>,<a href="#R8" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="R8">8</a>). By contrast, Shimokawa et al have advocated early surgery involving open distal replacement of the ascending aorta for all type A intramural hematomas. This recommendation is based on the results of their study, in which the risk of immediate surgical treatment was low, midterm results were acceptable, and 5-year survival was 100% (<a href="#R34" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="R34">34</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F13A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g13b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1458" aria-labelledby="F13B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13b.</b>  Type A aortic intramural hematoma at high risk for progression to dissection. <b>(a, b)</b> Unenhanced <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(b)</b> axial CT images demonstrate an ascending aortic intramural hematoma, with a maximal aortic diameter of 6.4 cm. The implicit high risk of progression to aortic dissection prompted surgical treatment. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced axial CT image obtained after surgical repair shows a normal caliber of the ascending aorta. hematomas, with frequent surveillance imaging and timely surgical repair in patients with complications. Further support for these recommendations may be found in the demographic characteristics of those affected by intramural hematoma (typically, older adults) and the potentially high morbidity and mortality associated with aortic surgery in this population (<a href="#R5" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="R5">5</a>,<a href="#R8" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="R8">8</a>). By contrast, Shimokawa et al have advocated early surgery involving open distal replacement of the ascending aorta for all type A intramural hematomas. This recommendation is based on the results of their study, in which the risk of immediate surgical treatment was low, midterm results were acceptable, and 5-year survival was 100% (<a href="#R34" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="R34">34</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F13B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g13c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1475" aria-labelledby="F13C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13c.</b>  Type A aortic intramural hematoma at high risk for progression to dissection. <b>(a, b)</b> Unenhanced <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced <b>(b)</b> axial CT images demonstrate an ascending aortic intramural hematoma, with a maximal aortic diameter of 6.4 cm. The implicit high risk of progression to aortic dissection prompted surgical treatment. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced axial CT image obtained after surgical repair shows a normal caliber of the ascending aorta. hematomas, with frequent surveillance imaging and timely surgical repair in patients with complications. Further support for these recommendations may be found in the demographic characteristics of those affected by intramural hematoma (typically, older adults) and the potentially high morbidity and mortality associated with aortic surgery in this population (<a href="#R5" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="R5">5</a>,<a href="#R8" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="R8">8</a>). By contrast, Shimokawa et al have advocated early surgery involving open distal replacement of the ascending aorta for all type A intramural hematomas. This recommendation is based on the results of their study, in which the risk of immediate surgical treatment was low, midterm results were acceptable, and 5-year survival was 100% (<a href="#R34" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="R34">34</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F13C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g14a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1676" aria-labelledby="F14A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14a.</b>  Late development of fusiform aneurysm in aortic intramural hematoma. <b>(a, b)</b> Unenhanced axial CT images obtained at presentation (<b>a</b> at a higher level than <b>b</b>) depict a type B hematoma. Conservative management ensued. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced axial CT image obtained 2 years later shows a fusiform aneurysm at the site of the initial aortic intramural hematoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F14A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g14b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1580" aria-labelledby="F14B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14b.</b>  Late development of fusiform aneurysm in aortic intramural hematoma. <b>(a, b)</b> Unenhanced axial CT images obtained at presentation (<b>a</b> at a higher level than <b>b</b>) depict a type B hematoma. Conservative management ensued. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced axial CT image obtained 2 years later shows a fusiform aneurysm at the site of the initial aortic intramural hematoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F14B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.293085122/asset/images/g09ma18g14c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1556" aria-labelledby="F14C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14c.</b>  Late development of fusiform aneurysm in aortic intramural hematoma. <b>(a, b)</b> Unenhanced axial CT images obtained at presentation (<b>a</b> at a higher level than <b>b</b>) depict a type B hematoma. Conservative management ensued. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced axial CT image obtained 2 years later shows a fusiform aneurysm at the site of the initial aortic intramural hematoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.293085122&amp;id=F14C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="R1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">Krukenberg</span><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-fnm">E</span></span>. Beitrage zur frage des aneurysma dissecans. <em>Beitr Pathol Anat Allg Pathol</em>1920; 67: 329–351.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Beitr+Pathol+Anat+Allg+Pathol&amp;publication_year=1920&amp;pages=329">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="R2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">Sawhney</span><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-fnm">NS</span></span>, DeMaria AN, Blanchard DG. Aortic intramural hematoma: an increasingly recognized and potentially fatal entity. <em>Chest</em>2001; 120: 1340–1346.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1378/chest.120.4.1340">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11591580/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Chest&amp;publication_year=2001&amp;pages=1340&amp;doi=10.1378%2Fchest.120.4.1340&amp;pmid=11591580">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><di